    notes:
      "## Form Selection — Critical Decision\n**KSM-66** (Ixoreal Biomed): Full-spectrum root extract, 5% withanolides, water-extracted. The most-studied form clinically — used in the majority of modern Ashwagandha RCTs (Chandrasekhar 2012, Wankhede 2015, Choudhary 2017, Salve 2019, Sharma 2018, Lopresti 2019). Standard 600mg dosing. Most appropriate when users want the most-validated form with the largest clinical trial database.\n\n**Sensoril** (Natreon): Root + leaf extract, 10% withanolides, higher withaferin A content. More potent per mg — typical dosing 125–250mg achieves comparable withanolide exposure to KSM-66 600mg. Often preferred for stress / cortisol applications specifically; the higher leaf-derived withaferin A may contribute to anti-inflammatory effects. Slightly more sedating than KSM-66 in subjective reports.\n\n**Shoden** (Arjuna Natural): 35% withanolides — the highest-potency commercial extract. Smaller dosing (60–120mg) achieves similar withanolide exposure to higher doses of KSM-66. Newer to market with smaller clinical database than KSM-66 but the published trials are positive (Pingali 2019, Vol 2020). Most appropriate for users prioritizing pill count or wanting to layer withanolide exposure with minimal capsule burden.\n\n**Crude powder** (no standardization): variable potency 1–3% withanolides typically; inferior to standardized extracts for clinical effect. Not recommended for clinical use — the price advantage doesn't compensate for variable bioactive load.\n\n## Beginner Protocol\nKSM-66 300mg/day × 1 week (PM dosing — start there to assess sedation), then 600mg/day. Track: subjective stress (1–10 scale daily), sleep quality (latency, efficiency, dream recall), mood, energy. Effects accumulate — assess at 4 and 8 weeks, not acutely. Bracket with comprehensive metabolic panel + thyroid panel (TSH, fT3, fT4) at baseline and 8 weeks if any thyroid concern in history.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\nLayer with: Rhodiola rosea 200–400mg AM (complementary mechanism — Ashwagandha calms, Rhodiola energizes; together they 'broaden the stress envelope'), magnesium glycinate 400mg PM (HPA-axis cofactor), L-theanine 200mg as needed for acute stress, phosphatidylserine 100–300mg PM for cortisol blunting at the right time of day. For T-support contexts: pair with Tongkat Ali 400mg AM, Cistanche 600mg/day. For sleep-priority contexts: pair with magnesium L-threonate 2g + glycine 3g + apigenin 50mg PM. The Ashwagandha + Rhodiola + magnesium triumvirate is the most evidence-supported foundational adaptogen stack.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nChandrasekhar 2012 (KSM-66, 600mg, 60 days, n=64 stressed adults): 27.9% morning cortisol reduction, significant PSS and DASS-42 improvements. Wankhede 2015 (KSM-66, 600mg, 8 weeks, n=57 resistance-training men): testosterone elevation, strength and lean mass improvements. Salve 2019 (KSM-66, 300mg BID, 8 weeks, n=60 with insomnia): improvements across all sleep architecture metrics. Lopresti 2019 (KSM-66, 240mg, 60 days, n=58 stressed adults): cortisol reduction, DHEA-S elevation, T elevation. Sharma 2018 (Ashwagandha root extract, 600mg, 8 weeks, n=50 subclinical hypothyroidism): TSH reduction, T3/T4 normalization.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nN/A — oral capsule or powder. With food to reduce rare GI sensitivity. Consistent timing supports protocol adherence.\n\n## Synergies\n**Rhodiola:** complementary stress-resilience mechanisms — Ashwagandha calms, Rhodiola energizes. **Magnesium glycinate:** HPA-axis cofactor support. **Cordyceps:** combined adaptogen stack for athletic performance. **Tongkat Ali:** combined T-support for stressed / overtrained men.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nStrongest evidence base of any adaptogen. 100+ published clinical trials across stress, sleep, anxiety, testosterone, athletic performance, fertility, cognitive function, thyroid, female reproductive health. Effect sizes modest but consistent across multiple high-quality RCTs. KSM-66 specifically has the largest clinical trial database.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: solid efficacy in stress and HPA-axis contexts; modest but consistent T elevation in stressed men; sleep and anxiety benefits well-documented; thyroid effects documented in subclinical hypothyroidism. Anecdote: overwhelmingly positive for stress / sleep / anxiety contexts; T-boost reports more variable (works best for stressed/overtrained men with low baseline; less impressive in already-optimized users — consistent with the trial evidence). Decision frame: foundational adaptogen for stress / sleep / anxiety contexts; useful adjunct in T-support stacks for users with stress-related low T; reasonable trial in subclinical hypothyroidism contexts under prescriber coordination.",
