    notes:
      "## Beginner Protocol\n1000mg/day (single AM dose or split) × 4 weeks. Track: training performance (cardio especially — endurance, time-to-exhaustion, recovery), energy, sleep. Effects often subtle first 2 weeks, more apparent at 4–6 weeks.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\nFor endurance athletes: dose-load 2000–3000mg/day for 4–6 weeks pre-competition phase, then continuous 1500mg/day maintenance. Stack with: Lion's Mane (cognitive performance + mushroom-class synergy), Reishi (sleep + immune complement), Ashwagandha (HPA-axis support during training stress), creatine 5g/day (different mechanism but complementary energy support). For high-altitude / hypoxic context (altitude training, mountain athletes): begin Cordyceps loading 4–6 weeks before exposure.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nChen 2010 (n=20 healthy older adults, 12 weeks, CS-4 333mg TID): improved VO2max, lactate threshold, ventilatory threshold. Hirsch 2017 (n=28 healthy younger trained adults, 1 week and 3 weeks, militaris 4g/day): improved time-to-exhaustion at 3 weeks. Earnest 2004 (n=12 trained cyclists, 5 weeks, CS-4 3g/day): no significant ergogenic effect — the mixed-results pattern characteristic of Cordyceps research. Some trials positive, some neutral.\n\n## Militaris vs Sinensis vs CS-4 — Decision Frame\n**Cordyceps militaris (cultivated):** practical commercial product; substantial cordycepin content (1–5% in good extracts); cost-effective; fruiting body extracts deliver the most reliable bioactive load.\n\n**Cordyceps sinensis / Ophiocordyceps sinensis (wild):** premium-priced (true wild sinensis is hundreds of dollars per ounce); supply chain difficult to verify; the prestige market for true sinensis is not the same market as the supplement-shelf 'sinensis' products.\n\n**CS-4 strain:** cultivated strain originally derived from sinensis isolate; pharmacologically intermediate; commercially viable alternative to true sinensis; appears in many 'sinensis' labeled products.\n\nFor practical supplement use: cultivated militaris fruiting body extracts deliver the best evidence-to-cost ratio.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nN/A — oral capsule, powder, or tincture. Powder mixes into coffee or smoothie reasonably (mild mushroom flavor). Tincture sublingual or in water. Capsule for convenience.\n\n## Synergies\n**Lion's Mane:** mushroom-stack pairing — different mechanisms, complementary effects (cognitive + endurance). **Reishi:** sleep + immune complement; the mushroom triumvirate. **Ashwagandha:** HPA-axis + adaptogen support during training stress. **Creatine:** complementary energy mechanism (PCr system vs mitochondrial).\n\n## Evidence Quality\nReasonable RCT evidence for endurance performance and VO2max — some positive trials, some neutral (effect size variable). Cordycepin pharmacology well-characterized in vitro and in animal models. Long traditional use history in Chinese medicine for energy/vitality/longevity contexts. Immune-modulation evidence is reasonable.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: modest endurance benefit documented in some RCTs, neutral in others — effect size varies by study, population, dose, and product quality. Anecdote: positive for endurance athletes (cardio improvement, recovery, breath capacity); mixed for general users (some report energy benefit, others note no clear effect). Decision frame: useful adjunct for endurance-focused athletes; less impressive for general adaptogen use vs Ashwagandha or Rhodiola; the immune-modulation case is reasonable for users prioritizing immune support.",
    tags: ["cordyceps", "cordyceps militaris", "cordyceps sinensis", "mushroom", "adaptogen", "endurance", "VO2max", "ATP", "cordycepin", "Chinese medicine", "altitude tolerance"],
