      "Edible medicinal mushroom (Hericium erinaceus) with distinctive cascading-spine fruiting body — the appearance gives rise to common names across cultures (Lion's Mane in English, Yamabushitake in Japanese after the Buddhist mountain monks whose robes the cascading spines resemble, Hou tou gu in Chinese = 'monkey head mushroom'). Used culinarily and medicinally in East Asian traditions for centuries; modern interest emerged from Japanese research in the 1990s identifying the small-molecule bioactives. **Active compounds**: hericenones (in fruiting body — hericenone B, C, D, E primarily) and erinacines (in mycelium — erinacine A, B, C, E primarily). Both compound classes are small molecules that cross the blood-brain barrier and stimulate nerve growth factor (NGF) and brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF) expression in CNS tissue. The fruiting body / mycelium distinction matters substantially for product selection — different bioactive populations in each. **Mechanism**: (1) hericenones / erinacines bind TrkA receptors on neurons, activating NGF-mimetic signaling cascades that drive neurite outgrowth, synaptic plasticity, and neurogenesis (particularly in hippocampus and forebrain cholinergic neurons); (2) BDNF elevation supporting cognitive plasticity and mood; (3) anti-inflammatory effects in CNS via NF-κB modulation; (4) myelin-sheath supportive effects (mechanism for peripheral nerve repair); (5) gut-brain axis modulation via β-glucan effects on gut microbiome and intestinal nervous system; (6) mild antioxidant effects in CNS tissue. **Animal evidence**: substantial neurogenesis effects in mouse hippocampus, accelerated peripheral nerve repair (sciatic nerve crush models), cognitive improvement in dementia models (5xFAD Alzheimer's mice), depressive-like behavior reduction in stress models. **Human evidence**: accumulating — small RCTs have shown cognitive improvement in mild cognitive impairment (Mori 2009 — the foundational human trial), modest improvements in healthy older adults, mood / anxiety benefits (Nagano 2010 menopausal symptoms), and emerging applications in depression and post-concussion recovery.",
