    notes:
      "## Beginner Protocol\n1000mg/day fruiting body extract × 8 weeks. Track: subjective cognitive performance (focus, memory, mental clarity, word retrieval), mood, anxiety, sleep quality. Effects often subtle initially — assess at 4 and 8 weeks rather than acute response. For users approaching this for cognitive longevity prevention, the 8-week initial trial demonstrates whether you're a responder; continue if benefit is clear.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\nLayer with Cordyceps (mushroom-class synergy + endurance) and Reishi (sleep + immune complement) for the 'mushroom triumvirate' approach common in nootropic stacks. Add Alpha-GPC 300–600mg for cholinergic substrate support, omega-3 high-DHA (1g+ DHA/day) for membrane support, magnesium L-threonate 2g pre-bed for CNS magnesium specifically, bacopa monnieri 300mg/day for complementary cognitive mechanism. Useful for: cognitive aging contexts, post-concussion recovery, demanding intellectual work, family history of dementia.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nMori 2009 (n=30, mild cognitive impairment, 16 weeks, 3g dried fruiting body powder/day): Hasegawa Dementia Scale-Revised (HDS-R) significantly improved at weeks 8, 12, 16; improvements regressed toward baseline 4 weeks after discontinuation. This is the foundational human cognitive trial. Nagano 2010 (n=30 menopausal women, 4 weeks, Lion's Mane cookies 2g/day): improvements in indefinite complaints scale (irritation, palpitations, sleep, concentration). Mori 2008 (n=30 healthy adults, 4 weeks): self-reported mood improvements. Saitsu 2019 (n=31 healthy older adults, 12 weeks): cognitive function improvements.\n\n## Fruiting Body vs Mycelium — Form Selection\n**Fruiting body extracts:** contain hericenones primarily; the fruiting body is what most people picture as 'mushroom'; preferred for cognitive applications based on hericenones' BBB penetration and NGF activity in human brain tissue.\n\n**Mycelium extracts:** contain erinacines primarily; the underground / substrate-grown vegetative phase; erinacines have stronger NGF activity in animal models but human relevance debated.\n\n**Dual extracts:** combine fruiting body + mycelium; theoretically capture both compound classes; many practitioners prefer this approach.\n\n**Mycelium-on-grain products:** the problematic category — mushroom mycelium grown on grain substrate (rice, oats), then dried and powdered together. Reported mushroom content typically counts the grain weight; actual hericenone / erinacine content is low. Avoid these products.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nN/A — oral capsule, powder (mushroom-flavored, mixes into coffee), tincture, or whole fresh mushroom culinary preparation. Fresh sautéed Lion's Mane in butter is genuinely delicious — culinary use is a real option if accessible.\n\n## Synergies\n**Cordyceps + Reishi:** mushroom triumvirate — different mechanisms, complementary CNS + energy + immune effects. **Alpha-GPC:** cholinergic substrate. **Omega-3 DHA:** membrane lipid for neural function. **Magnesium L-threonate:** CNS magnesium specifically. **Bacopa monnieri:** complementary cognitive mechanism via different pathway.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nReasonable evidence for cognitive improvement in MCI; emerging evidence in healthy aging, mood/anxiety, peripheral nerve repair. Animal data on neurogenesis is robust; human translation accumulating but not yet large-scale RCT.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: solid mechanistic case for NGF/BDNF stimulation; clinical trials showing cognitive improvement in MCI; mood / anxiety benefits documented in smaller studies; peripheral nerve repair animal data robust. Anecdote: extensive nootropic-community use; reports overwhelmingly positive on subjective cognitive performance with consistent use; quality of product matters substantially. Decision frame: foundational nootropic for cognitive longevity contexts; useful for any user prioritizing brain health, family history of dementia, or post-concussion recovery.",
