    mechanism:
      "Southeast Asian shrub (Eurycoma longifolia) used traditionally in Malaysian, Indonesian, and Vietnamese medicine for vitality, fertility, and 'male tonic' applications — the name 'Tongkat Ali' translates roughly as 'Ali's walking stick' in Malay, referring to the tall straight root and its restorative reputation. **Active compounds**: quassinoids (eurycomanone primary, plus eurycomanol, longilactone, eurycolactone, eurycomalactone), peptides (eurypeptides — small bioactive peptides), alkaloids (canthin-6-one alkaloids), glycosaponins, polysaccharides. Eurycomanone is the most-studied bioactive and the basis for standardization in clinical-grade extracts. **Mechanism (testosterone support — primary effect)**: (1) **SHBG (sex hormone binding globulin) modulation** — Tongkat Ali appears to reduce SHBG binding capacity, increasing free testosterone fraction without necessarily changing total T; this is the most-documented mechanism and explains the consistent free-T elevation across studies despite variable total-T effects; (2) **Leydig cell steroidogenesis support** — direct testicular effects increasing T production capacity; (3) **modest cortisol reduction** — the testosterone:cortisol ratio improvement is more consistent than absolute T elevation in many studies, supporting the 'stress-related low T' use case specifically; (4) **aromatase inhibition** — modest reduction in T-to-estradiol conversion; (5) **eurypeptide effects on androgen receptor sensitivity** in some animal studies. **Mechanism (broader)**: adaptogenic stress response, mild immunomodulation, improved sperm parameters (count, motility, morphology) in fertility studies, modest effects on body composition in older men. **Standardization is critical** — eurycomanone-standardized extracts (typically 1–2% eurycomanone) are pharmacologically active. **Physta** (the Malaysian Forest Research Institute's water-extracted, eurycomanone-standardized extract) is the gold standard — used in the majority of clinical trials including Tambi 2012, Henkel 2014, Talbott 2013, Ismail 2012. Lower-grade products labeled '100:1' or '200:1' extract ratios may be variably potent depending on extraction method and source material.",
