      "## Beginner Protocol\n1000mg/day × 8 weeks, particularly relevant for users with elevated baseline liver enzymes or hepatotoxic exposure context (alcohol use, AAS users, hepatotoxic medications, NAFLD). Bracket with comprehensive liver panel (ALT, AST, GGT, bilirubin) at baseline and 8 weeks.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\nLayer with TUDCA 250–500mg/day (bile acid liver support, complementary mechanism), milk thistle (silymarin) 250mg/day (the most-studied hepatoprotective herb), N-acetylcysteine (NAC) 600mg/day (glutathione substrate). The Schisandra + TUDCA + NAC + milk thistle stack is the comprehensive liver-support protocol for users with hepatotoxic exposure. **AAS users specifically benefit** from this stack during oral cycles (Anavar, Anadrol, Stanozolol, Dianabol) — the 17α-alkylation hepatic burden is real, and the liver-support stack mitigates measurable damage. Eleuthero pairs naturally for the broader Russian-medicine adaptogen approach.\n\n## CYP3A4 Drug Interaction Note\nSchisandra is one of the more clinically meaningful herb-drug interaction risks in the supplement landscape. CYP3A4 modulation affects ~50% of clinically-used medications. Users on chronic medications (statins, calcium channel blockers, immunosuppressants, antiretrovirals, certain antibiotics, psychotropics) should coordinate with prescriber before initiating. The interaction is not necessarily severe but is documented and predictable.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nN/A — oral capsule, powder, tincture, or whole dried berry. Whole-berry preparation: 1–2 tablespoons dried berries simmered in water 20 minutes for tea; produces the characteristic 'five flavor' experience.\n\n## Synergies\n**Eleuthero:** traditional Russian / Chinese medicine pairing — both are foundational Soviet adaptogens. **TUDCA:** bile acid liver support; complementary hepatoprotective mechanism. **Milk thistle:** silymarin antioxidant hepatoprotective mechanism. **NAC:** glutathione substrate for phase II detoxification.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nReasonable evidence base for hepatoprotection (animal data robust, human clinical evidence accumulating). Adaptogen effects less robust than Ashwagandha or Rhodiola. CYP3A4 modulation well-documented in PK studies.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: solid hepatoprotective evidence base; modest adaptogen effects; well-characterized CYP3A4 interaction. Anecdote: positive in liver-support contexts (AAS users, alcohol contexts, elevated enzymes); less remarkable as a primary adaptogen. Decision frame: foundational liver-support compound; useful adaptogen adjunct in Russian-medicine-style protocols; CYP3A4 interaction warrants prescriber awareness for users on chronic medications.",
